A developer’s honest breakdown of the exact tools, code, and decisions that turned side projects into recurring income
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Three years ago I was writing JavaScript for a paycheck like everyone else — tickets in, tickets out, sprint over, repeat. Somewhere around year two, I got tired of building things that only made money for someone else’s company. So I started building small things that made money for me.
None of these were unicorn ideas. No VC pitch decks, no “disrupting an industry” nonsense. Just JavaScript, some APIs, and a willingness to ship ugly things fast. This is the real breakdown — code included — of what actually worked, what didn’t, and why.

1) The Price-Tracking Bot That Started It All
It began with something dumb: I wanted a graphics card that kept selling out the second it restocked. Instead of refreshing a page like a caveman, I wrote a script.
import puppeteer from "puppeteer";
import nodemailer from "nodemailer";const PRODUCT_URL = "https://example-store.com/product/rtx-4080";
async function checkStock() {
const browser = await puppeteer.launch({ headless: "new" });
const page = await browser.newPage();
await page.goto(PRODUCT_URL, { waitUntil: "networkidle2" });
const inStock = await page.evaluate(() => {
const button = document.querySelector("[data-testid='add-to-cart']");
return button && !button.disabled;
});
await browser.close();
return inStock;
}
async function notify(subject, text) {
const transporter = nodemailer.createTransport({
service: "gmail",
auth: {
user: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
pass: process.env.EMAIL_PASS,
},
});
await transporter.sendMail({
from: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
to: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
subject,
text,
});
}
async function main() {
console.log("Checking stock...");
const available = await checkStock();
if (available) {
console.log("IN STOCK — notifying");
await notify("GPU is in stock!", `Grab it now: ${PRODUCT_URL}`);
} else {
console.log("Still out of stock.");
}
}
setInterval(main, 1000 * 60 * 5); // every 5 minutes
main();
I got the card. Then a friend asked me to track sneakers. Then another asked about concert tickets. That’s when it clicked — this wasn’t a personal tool anymore, it was a product. I turned it into a small paid service where people submit a URL and a Discord webhook, and I run the checks server-side on a cron job. $6/month per tracked item, no infrastructure beyond a $5 VPS.

2) Turning a Node Script Into a Chrome Extension People Pay For
Puppeteer scripts are great until your “customers” are non-technical and don’t want to run Node on their laptop. So I rebuilt the stock-checker logic as a Chrome extension, which is a completely different beast — no server, no Puppeteer, just content scripts and the extension messaging API.
// content-script.js
function extractPrice() {
const priceEl = document.querySelector(".price-current");
if (!priceEl) return null;
return parseFloat(priceEl.textContent.replace(/[^0-9.]/g, ""));
}chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((message, sender, sendResponse) => {
if (message.type === "GET_PRICE") {
sendResponse({ price: extractPrice() });
}
return true;
});
// background.js
const trackedItems = {};chrome.alarms.create("priceCheck", { periodInMinutes: 15 });
chrome.alarms.onAlarm.addListener(async (alarm) => {
if (alarm.name !== "priceCheck") return;
for (const [tabUrl, lastPrice] of Object.entries(trackedItems)) {
const tabs = await chrome.tabs.query({ url: tabUrl });
if (tabs.length === 0) continue;
chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tabs[0].id, { type: "GET_PRICE" }, (response) => {
if (response && response.price && response.price < lastPrice) {
chrome.notifications.create({
type: "basic",
iconUrl: "icon.png",
title: "Price Drop!",
message: `Price dropped to $${response.price}`,
});
trackedItems[tabUrl] = response.price;
}
});
}
});
I gated the “track unlimited items” feature behind a $4/month Stripe subscription using Chrome’s chrome.identity API to link users to their Stripe customer ID. Free users get 1 tracked item, paid users get unlimited. Extension revenue isn't glamorous, but it's genuinely passive — no support tickets, no servers to babysit.

3) The API Wrapper Nobody Wanted to Build Themselves
Some money doesn’t come from a flashy product — it comes from doing the annoying integration work other developers don’t want to touch. I noticed a lot of indie devs needed to convert currencies for invoices but didn’t want to deal with rate-limited free APIs or inconsistent formats. So I built a thin, reliable wrapper and sold access to it.
import express from "express";
import axios from "axios";
import NodeCache from "node-cache";
import rateLimit from "express-rate-limit";const app = express();
const cache = new NodeCache({ stdTTL: 3600 }); // cache rates for 1 hour
const limiter = rateLimit({
windowMs: 60 * 1000,
max: 30,
message: { error: "Rate limit exceeded" },
});
app.use(limiter);
app.use(express.json());
async function fetchRates(base) {
const cached = cache.get(base);
if (cached) return cached;
const response = await axios.get(
`https://open.er-api.com/v6/latest/${base}`
);
const rates = response.data.rates;
cache.set(base, rates);
return rates;
}
app.get("/api/convert", async (req, res) => {
const { from, to, amount } = req.query;
if (!from || !to || !amount) {
return res.status(400).json({ error: "Missing parameters" });
}
try {
const rates = await fetchRates(from.toUpperCase());
const rate = rates[to.toUpperCase()];
if (!rate) {
return res.status(404).json({ error: "Currency not supported" });
}
const converted = parseFloat(amount) * rate;
res.json({
from,
to,
amount: parseFloat(amount),
rate,
converted: parseFloat(converted.toFixed(2)),
});
} catch (err) {
res.status(500).json({ error: "Conversion failed" });
}
});
app.listen(3000, () => console.log("Currency API running on port 3000"));
I put this behind an API-key middleware and sold tiered access on RapidAPI. It’s not much per call, but at volume, boring infrastructure like this adds up because the marginal cost of serving one more request is basically nothing.

4) A Slack Bot That Automated My Freelance Invoicing
Freelancing meant I was manually tracking hours, calculating totals, and generating invoices in a spreadsheet like it was 2009. So I built a Slack bot that does the whole thing from a chat command.
import { App } from "@slack/bolt";
import PDFDocument from "pdfkit";
import fs from "fs";const app = new App({
token: process.env.SLACK_BOT_TOKEN,
signingSecret: process.env.SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET,
socketMode: true,
appToken: process.env.SLACK_APP_TOKEN,
});
app.command("/invoice", async ({ command, ack, respond }) => {
await ack();
const [client, hoursStr, rateStr] = command.text.split(",").map((s) => s.trim());
const hours = parseFloat(hoursStr);
const rate = parseFloat(rateStr);
const total = hours * rate;
const doc = new PDFDocument();
const filePath = `./invoices/${client}-${Date.now()}.pdf`;
doc.pipe(fs.createWriteStream(filePath));
doc.fontSize(20).text("Invoice", { align: "center" });
doc.moveDown();
doc.fontSize(12).text(`Client: ${client}`);
doc.text(`Hours worked: ${hours}`);
doc.text(`Hourly rate: $${rate}`);
doc.text(`Total due: $${total.toFixed(2)}`);
doc.end();
await respond(`Invoice generated for ${client}: $${total.toFixed(2)}`);
});
(async () => {
await app.start();
console.log("Invoice bot is running!");
})();
Typing /invoice Acme Corp, 12, 85 in Slack now spits out a formatted PDF invoice in under two seconds. I don't sell this one — it saves me money instead of making it — but I mention it because "tools that save you time" and "tools that make you money" are the same category of asset once you zoom out far enough.

5) The Newsletter Scraper That Turned Into a Paid Digest
I used to manually read a dozen tech newsletters every morning and mentally summarize the interesting bits for a small Discord community I run. Eventually I automated the whole pipeline — fetch, parse, summarize, publish — and turned the output into a paid daily digest.
import Parser from "rss-parser";
import { OpenAI } from "openai";
import fs from "fs";const parser = new Parser();
const openai = new OpenAI({ apiKey: process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY });
const FEEDS = [
"https://example-newsletter.com/rss",
"https://another-source.com/feed.xml",
];
async function fetchArticles() {
const allItems = [];
for (const feedUrl of FEEDS) {
const feed = await parser.parseURL(feedUrl);
const recent = feed.items.slice(0, 3);
allItems.push(...recent);
}
return allItems;
}
async function summarizeArticles(articles) {
const combinedText = articles
.map((a) => `Title: ${a.title}\nContent: ${a.contentSnippet}`)
.join("\n\n");
const response = await openai.chat.completions.create({
model: "gpt-4o-mini",
messages: [
{
role: "system",
content: "Summarize these tech articles into 5 concise bullet points, focused on what a developer would find actionable.",
},
{ role: "user", content: combinedText },
],
temperature: 0.3,
});
return response.choices[0].message.content;
}
async function main() {
const articles = await fetchArticles();
const summary = await summarizeArticles(articles);
const digest = `# Daily Dev Digest — ${new Date().toDateString()}\n\n${summary}`;
fs.writeFileSync("./digest.md", digest);
console.log("Digest generated:");
console.log(digest);
}
main();
This runs every morning via a cron job, gets pushed to a private newsletter platform, and now funds a decent chunk of my coffee habit through paid subscriptions. The lesson here wasn’t the code — it was noticing that people will pay to have their time given back to them.

6) Turning Webhooks Into Passive Income With Stripe
None of the above matters if you can’t actually collect money reliably. Every paid tool I’ve built routes through the same Stripe webhook handler, refined over dozens of bugs into something boring and dependable.
import express from "express";
import Stripe from "stripe";const app = express();
const stripe = new Stripe(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY);
const endpointSecret = process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET;
app.post(
"/webhook",
express.raw({ type: "application/json" }),
(req, res) => {
const sig = req.headers["stripe-signature"];
let event;
try {
event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(req.body, sig, endpointSecret);
} catch (err) {
console.log(`Webhook signature verification failed: ${err.message}`);
return res.sendStatus(400);
}
switch (event.type) {
case "checkout.session.completed": {
const session = event.data.object;
grantAccess(session.customer_email);
break;
}
case "customer.subscription.deleted": {
const subscription = event.data.object;
revokeAccess(subscription.customer);
break;
}
default:
console.log(`Unhandled event type: ${event.type}`);
}
res.json({ received: true });
}
);
function grantAccess(email) {
console.log(`Granting access to ${email}`);
// insert into database, send welcome email, etc.
}
function revokeAccess(customerId) {
console.log(`Revoking access for customer ${customerId}`);
// remove access, downgrade permissions, etc.
}
app.listen(4000, () => console.log("Webhook server running on port 4000"));
Boring code. Zero personality. This is also the single most important file across all five projects, because it’s the difference between “I built a cool tool” and “I built a business.”

7) Monitoring Everything With a Single Dashboard Script
Once you have more than one revenue stream, you need to know what’s actually working without logging into five different dashboards every day. I built a tiny internal tool that pulls numbers from each service and puts them in one place.
